›››                 ăč14EMISSION CONTROLăč15›››     Emission control is the process in trying to reduce the level of harmful gasses in engine exhaust.››     Air pollution results when atmospheric conditions trap and concentrate polluted or contaminated air.››    There are two types of pollution. Natural and man-made. Natural pollution includes smoke from forest and grass fires, gasses given off by decomposing matter, windblown dust and dirt, and ashes and stuff from volcanic eruptions. Man-made pollution is caused mainly by the burning of fuel to produce heat and power.››    Man-made pollution can cause serious health problems such as respiratory irritations, eye irritations, asthma, cancer, emphysema, circulatory problems, skin problems, severe headaches, and even death. Pollution can even damage buildings and wildlife.› ›    It is very important that we reduce air pollution because not only is it harming us now but it can harm people in future generations. If air pollution continues we might even kill off the human race.››    It take great technology and mechanics with good attitudes who are willing to learn are always in a great demand to work on emission control devices.››    Major emission control deviceson cars today include evaporative emission control, pcv system, fuel system modifications and controls, combustion controls, exhaust gas recirculation (EGR), air injection, and catalytic converters.››    Any tamperingwith the emission control systems, except by a qualified mechanic, can severely effect engine and car performance.››    All in all emission control is a pretty serious problem that we must face with on cars today.›››                 THE END›› 